<H2>Triple Plays 1871-99</H2>
<P>Chuck Rosciam, Frank Hamilton and many others have developed
what we think is a complete list of all triple plays in the major
leagues since 1871, the start of the National Association.

<br><a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/TP1900-24.htm">1900-24</a>
<br><a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/TP1925-49.htm">1925-49</a>
<br><a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/TP1950-74.htm">1950-74</a>
<br><a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/TP1975-99.htm">1975-99</a>
<br><a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/TriplePlays.htm">2000-</a>

<p>
The By column shows the team that made the triple play.<br>
The Occ column indicates which bases were occupied.<br>
Scoring is the Retrosheet scoring code for the play or a variation of it. Some of the features, which may not apply to the variation:<br>
<ul>
<li>In the portion before the period, if any, (B),(1),(2),(3) show who was out on the play: batter, runners on which bases. If it is a ground ball triple play, indicated by GTP, the last play is on the batter if that is not indicated.
<li>After the period, runners being put out are indicated by runner X base out at as in 1X2 showing the runner on first was out going to second. The play is indicated in the following parentheses.
<li>GTP indicates a ground ball TP, LTP shows a line drive TP, BP means bunt pop up, FL indicates a foul ball caught.
<li>There may be a hit type and location such as /L9S, which would be for a line drive to short right field.
<li>An outstanding play is indicated by a + or ! after the fielder as in /L1+ showing the pitcher made a great catch of the line drive.
<li>A # at the end indicates some uncertainty about the play.
</ul>

<p>
We could use some help filling in the missing entries.
<p><b>Plays not allowed under current rules</b>: In the 19th Century, two types of plays not allowed under current rules could result in double or triple plays. The plays were dropping a third strike with a runner on first and less than two outs, which was prohibited in 1887, and intentionally not catching an pop up, which is prohibited by the infield fly rule adopted in 1895. A <a href="https://sabr.org/research/dropped-third-strike-life-and-times-rule">SABR article</a> has an extensive discuss about the history of these rules. A triple play with "K+E2" in the scoring below indicates a dropped third strike. One with an "E4", "E6", or another error shows one that now would be an infield fly rule out. None of these are real errors. There may be other such plays not so indicated.
